'''Anthony Ralston''' (born 16 November 1998) is a Scottish professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[right-back]] for {{Scottish football updater|Celtic}} club [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]].

==Club career==
Part of the youth system at [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] since the age of eight,<ref name="Delight21"/> Ralston made his debut for the first team on 11 May 2016, in a 2–1 defeat against [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36200297 |first=Scott |last=Davie |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=11 May 2016 |accessdate=26 May 2016 |title=St Johnstone 2–1 Celtic}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club in a 5–0 [[Scottish League Cup]] win over [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] on 8 August 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40829930|title=Celtic 5-0 Kilmarnock|publisher=BBC|date=8 August 2017 |accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref> He made further appearances early in the 2017–18 season, including a [[UEFA Champions League]] match against [[Paris Saint-Germain FC|Paris Saint-Germain]],<ref>{{cite news|date=12 September 2017|title=PSG ace Neymar blanks Celtic teen Anthony Ralston as he tries to shake his hand|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/psg-superstar-neymar-blanks-celtic-11159892|access-date=16 November 2021|website=Daily Record}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11945/11033447/neymar-just-another-player-says-celtics-anthony-ralston-after-pair-clash-in-champions-league|title=Neymar just another player, says Celtic's Anthony Ralston after pair clash in Champions League|last=Thomas|first=Lyall|date=13 September 2017|publisher=Sky Sports News|access-date=12 October 2025}}</ref> but then suffered a knee injury in late September.<ref name = "2022 contract"/> Ralston signed a long-term contract with Celtic in December 2017, with the deal due to run until the end of the 2021–22 season.<ref name = "2022 contract">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42501429 |title=Celtic full-back Anthony Ralston signs deal until 2022 |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=28 December 2017 |accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref>

On 16 March 2018, Ralston joined [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] on an emergency loan until the end of the 2017–18 season, a side challenging for promotion from the Championship up to the Premiership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/14098|title=Anthony Ralston joins Dundee United on emergency loan|publisher=[[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]|date=16 March 2018|accessdate=16 March 2018}}</ref> He made his debut on 20 March, in a 3–2 loss in the league to [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]].<ref name="arab">{{cite web |title=Tony Ralston - Player Profile |url=https://www.arabarchive.co.uk/player.php?id=1919 |website=Arab Archive |access-date=16 November 2021}}</ref> In 15 appearances, he helped United reach the semi-final play-off for promotion, scoring two goals, albeit the side lost to [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]] in the semi-final play-off.<ref name="arab" />

On 2 September 2019, Ralston moved to St Johnstone on a season-long loan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ralston joins on-loan|url=https://www.perthstjohnstonefc.co.uk/news/post/ralston-joins-loan|publisher=St Johnstone F.C.|date=2 September 2019|accessdate=2 September 2019}}</ref> Upon his return from the St Johnstone loan, Ralston played in only one game for Celtic during the following season, coming in a 0–0 draw against [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]] when several squad regulars were missing due to a [[COVID-19]] isolation issue,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/55598659|title=Celtic 0–0 Livingston|website=bbc.co.uk|first=Martin|last=Watt|date=17 January 2021|access-date= 30 July 2021}}</ref> and when centre-half [[Kristoffer Ajer]] then loanee [[Jonjoe Kenny]] were selected at right-back ahead of him following the sale of [[Jeremie Frimpong]], it appeared his time with the club would be coming to an end.<ref name="Heroics21"/>

At the start of the [[2021–22 Celtic F.C. season|2021–22 season]] under new manager [[Ange Postecoglou]], Ralston signed a contract extension until May 2022 and started in both legs against [[FC Midtjylland]] in the [[2021–22 UEFA Champions League qualifying phase and play-off round#Second qualifying round|UEFA Champions League second qualifying round]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57855563|title=Celtic 1–1 FC Midtjylland|website=bbc.co.uk|first=Martin|last=Watt|date=20 July 2021|access-date=30 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57972180|title=FC Midtjylland 2–1 Celtic|website=bbc.co.uk|first=Thomas|last=Duncan|date=28 July 2021|access-date=30 July 2021}}</ref> Media outlets praised his performances in the early part of the season, following goals against [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] and [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58261406|title=Celtic: Tom Rogic & Anthony Ralston have revived careers under Ange Postecoglou|first=Thomas|last=Duncan|date=18 August 2021|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 2 November 2021, he signed a new long-term contract with Celtic, keeping him at the club until 2025.<ref name="Delight21">{{cite web|url=https://www.celticfc.com/news/2021/november/02/delight-as-anthony-ralston-signs-new-celtic-contract/|title=Delight as Anthony Ralston signs new Celtic contract|publisher=Celtic FC|date=2 November 2021|accessdate=2 November 2021}}</ref><ref name="Heroics21">{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/anthony-ralston-pens-celtic-extension-25360715 |title=Anthony Ralston signs Celtic contract extension as reward for early season heroics|last=Pirie|first=Mark|work=Daily Record|date=2 November 2021|accessdate=14 November 2021}}</ref>

On 15 December 2021, Ralston headed in a 97th-minute winner against [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]] in a 2–1 away victory for a Celtic side that had been reduced to ten men.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Celtic beat County with last-gasp goal |date=15 December 2021 |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59573754 |access-date=31 December 2022}}</ref> It has been assessed as one of the most important moments of the season for Celtic as they went on to win the [[2021–22 Scottish Premiership|2021-22 Scottish Premiership]] title, as the result kept them within touching distance of [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] who were four points ahead in the table at that time.<ref>{{Cite web |title=How did Celtic win the Scottish Premiership? Five key reasons for Ange Postecoglou's title success |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/soccer/news/celtic-win-scottish-premiership-reasons-postecoglou/cqnzo5jejzqccmy4dumeuokt |access-date=31 December 2022 |website=www.sportingnews.com |date=5 November 2022 }}</ref> At the end of 2022, Celtic signed Canadian [[Alistair Johnston]] who quickly became the first-choice right-back, with Ralston's role becoming that of a dependable back-up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/ralston-johnston-hartson-celtic-scotland-33917054|title=Ralston has 'huge respect' of pundit as Celtic lack of games down to one reason|first=Alan|last=Galindo|date=17 October 2024|website=Daily Record}}</ref>

On 26 September 2023, Ralston signed a new four-year contract with Celtic, keeping him at the club until 2027.<ref>{{Cite web|publisher=Celtic FC|title=Anthony Ralston signs new four-year deal with the Hoops|url=https://www.celticfc.com/news/2023/september/26/anthony-ralston-signs-new-four-year-deal-with-the-hoops/# |access-date=26 September 2023|date=26 September 2023|website=www.celticfc.com}}</ref>

==International career==
Ralston was involved with several Scotland youth squads up to the [[Scotland national under-21 football team|under-21s]].<ref>{{SFA player|143001}}</ref>

Selected for the [[Scotland national under-20 football team|Scotland under-20]] squad in the [[2017 Toulon Tournament]],<ref>{{ cite web | title = Scotland squad for Toulon announced | url = http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_fa_news.cfm?page=1957&newsCategoryID=6&newsID=16955 | publisher = [[Scottish Football Association]] | date = 17 May 2017 | access-date = 3 July 2022 }}</ref> Ralston played as Scotland beat [[Brazil national under-20 football team|Brazil under-20]]s 1–0, which was the nations first ever win against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] at any level.<ref>{{ cite web | url = https://www.glasgowtimes.co.uk/sport/15330314.amp/ | title = Toulon semi-final spot would be a dream for Celtic youngster Anthony Ralston | newspaper = [[Glasgow Times]] | date = 6 June 2017 | access-date = 3 July 2022 }}</ref> The team went on to claim the bronze medal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/news/scotland-finish-third-at-toulon-tournament-with-3-0-win/ | title = Scotland finish third at Toulon Tournament with 3-0 win | publisher = [[Scottish Football Association]] | date = 10 June 2017 |access-date = 1 July 2022}}</ref> It was the nations first ever medal at the competition.<ref>{{ cite web | title = JULES AND HOLSGROVE TAKE BRONZE WITH SCOTLAND IN TOULON | url = https://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/2017/june/jules-and-holsgrove-take-bronze-with-scotland-in-toulon/ | publisher = Reading FC | date = 11 June 2017 | access-date = 1 July 2022 }}</ref> Selected for the [[2018 Toulon Tournament squads#Group B|under-21 squad]] in the [[2018 Toulon Tournament]].<ref>{{ cite web | title=Scotland Under-21 squad announced for Toulon tournament | url = https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/news/scotland-under-21-squad-announced-for-toulon-tournament/ | publisher = [[Scottish Football Association]] | date = 3 May 2018 | access-date = 3 July 2022 }}</ref> They lost to [[Turkey national under-21 football team|Turkey under-21]]s in a penalty-out and finished fourth.<ref>{{ cite web | url = https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/news/scotland-finish-fourth-at-the-toulon-tournament-after-shoot-out-defeat-to-turkey/ | title = Scotland finish fourth at the Toulon tournament after shoot-out defeat to Turkey | publisher = [[Scottish Football Association]] | date = 10 June 2018 |access-date = 1 July 2022 }}</ref>

In November 2021, he was called up to the [[Scotland national football team|senior squad]] for the first time ahead of a [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group F|2022 World Cup qualifier]] against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]], as a replacement for the suspended [[Nathan Patterson (footballer)|Nathan Patterson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/celtic/celtics-anthony-ralston-called-for-scotland-duty-against-denmark-3457136|title=Celtic's Anthony Ralston called for Scotland duty against Denmark|work=The Scotsman|date=13 November 2021|accessdate=14 November 2021}}</ref> He made his international debut in the match<ref>{{Cite news|title=Scotland 2-0 Denmark: John Souttar and Che Adams fire Tartan Army to home World Cup play-off|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/scotland-vs-denmark/report/441762|access-date=16 November 2021|website=Sky Sports|language=en}}</ref> as a late substitute for [[Kieran Tierney]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59202146|title=Scotland beat Danes to earn home play-off|last=Lindsay|first=Clive|date=15 November 2021|publisher=BBC Sport|access-date=16 November 2021}}</ref> On his second Scotland appearance he scored his first international goal during a [[2022–23 UEFA Nations League]] group match against [[Armenia national football team|Armenia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/61740982 |title=Scotland 2-0 Armenia: Anthony Ralston revels in special first start at Hampden |last=Moffat |first=Colin |date=8 June 2022 |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=9 June 2022}}</ref>

On 7 June 2024, Ralston was named in Scotland's squad for the [[UEFA Euro 2024]] finals in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/record-breaking-goalkeeper-gordon-out-scotland-euro-2024-squad-2024-06-07/|title=Record-breaking goalkeeper Gordon out of Scotland's Euro 2024 squad|date=7 June 2024|access-date=15 June 2024|website=Reuters}}</ref> A week later, he started the opening match of the tournament, where Scotland lost 5–1 to hosts [[Germany national football team|Germany]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c844x4y3ee3t|title=Ruthless Germany humble 10-man Scotland in Euro 2024 opener|website=BBC Sport|access-date=15 June 2024}}</ref> He went on to start in both the second match against [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] and the third against [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] as Scotland finished bottom of [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group A|Group A]] with one point from three matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028e-1b2c127c5b92-e020507872a2-1000--scotland-1-1-switzerland-clarke-s-men-keep-group-a-hopes-/|title=Scotland 1-1 Switzerland: Clarke's men keep Group A hopes alive|access-date=24 June 2024|website=UEFA}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/match/2036186--scotland-vs-hungary/lineups/|title=Scotland vs Hungary: Line-ups|access-date=24 June 2024|website=UEFA}}</ref>

